A Beanstalk project is a directory tree with one strict config file, a source entry root, and generated output folders.

### Project root contents

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    project-root/
    ├── config.bst
    ├── src/
    │   └── #page.bst
    ├── lib/
    ├── dev/
    │   └── .beanstalk_manifest
    ├── release/
    │   └── .beanstalk_manifest
    └── .gitignore
]

### Directory roles

- `config.bst` is the only project config file. It lives at the project root and is not module source.
- The configured `entry_root` (usually `src`) is the source folder the compiler searches for module roots.
- `lib/` is the conventional default folder for project-local source libraries. Each direct child becomes an import prefix.
- `dev/` and `release/` are builder output folders, not source folders. They are generated and managed by the build system.
- `.beanstalk_manifest` files are build-system metadata used for safe stale-output cleanup. They are not source.

### Hash-root files inside source directories

A non-config file whose name starts with `#` and ends with `.bst` is a module root. The filename after `#` has no language-level semantic role. `#page.bst`, `#mod.bst`, `#api.bst` and `#anything.bst` are all equivalent root filenames.

The `bean new html` scaffold generates `src/#page.bst` as a conventional default. That convention does not make `#page.bst` a special compiler role. Any `#*.bst` filename in a source directory marks that directory as a module root.

### Source versus output

Source directories are owned by the developer. Output folders are generated by the builder and should be treated as build artifacts, not source. The builder owns stale-output cleanup for generated artifacts.

### Builder-neutral frontend versus builder-owned output

The compiler frontend discovers modules, resolves imports, checks types, lowers code and validates borrowing. A project builder then decides how compiled modules become real output files. The current user-facing builder is the HTML project builder.

This separation means the same frontend can later feed other builders. The frontend does not decide which modules produce artifacts. That decision belongs to the builder.

### Only config.bst has config semantics

No other filename has config meaning. `#config.bst` is a module root, not a config file. Alternate config filenames, compatibility handling and config-specific diagnostics for other names are not supported.

